ft">7 (32%)</td><td align="left">6 (26%)</td><td align="left">ns</td></tr><tr><td align="left">&#x02003;IV</td><td align="left">11 (50%)</td><td align="left">14 (61%)</td><td align="left">ns</td></tr><tr><td align="left">&#x02003;V</td><td align="left">1 (4%)</td><td align="left">1 (4%)</td><td align="left">ns</td></tr></tbody></table><table-wrap-foot><p>*median and interquartile range, ns: no statistical significance (<italic>P </italic>&#x0003e;0.05)</p><p>MPDN: methyl-prednisolone. SAPS: Simplified acute physiology score.</p></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap><p>Data concerning the microbiological findings are summarized in Table <xref ref-type="table" rid="T2">2</xref>. <italic>Streptococcus pneumoniae </italic>and <italic>Legionella pneumophila </italic>were the most common aetiologies. No statistically significant differences in aetiology were observed between the two groups, although pneumococcal pneumonia was more frequent in the placebo group. A definitive etiological diagnosis was obtained in 25 (55.6%) cases and a presumptive diagnosis in 11 (24.4%) additional episodes. No etiological diagnosis could be made in nine (20%) cases.</p><table-wrap id="T2" position="float"><label>Table 2</label><caption><p>Causative organisms</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left">Microorganisms</th><th align="left">Placebo</th><th align="left">MPDN</th><th align="left">Total</th><th align="left">
